Southern California faced severe weather conditions, with floods, mudslides, and power outages causing chaos.
In San Bernardino National Forest, cars were stranded in snow, while residents of Santa Clarita were evacuated due to floods.
Tragedy struck in Los Angeles when a hillside collapsed, burying two men in a tent, resulting in one death.
Rescue efforts were widespread, with over 170 people rescued from snow-trapped cars near Big Bear.
Major roads were closed, and Union Pacific faced rail line closures due to mudslides.
The region grappled with the aftermath of the storms, with more challenges expected.
